</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="FFC84D36FFCF8D022859CE5D2FB4FBB2" authorityName="Desutter-Grandcolas &amp; Hubbell" authorityYear="1993" box="[319,462,1024,1045]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Mayagryllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0ABCEAA7FFCF8D022859CE5D2FB4FBB2" box="[319,462,1024,1045]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="58">Mayagryllus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="FFC84D36FFCF8D02288CCE5C2CFCFBB1" authorityName="Desutter-Grandcolas &amp; Hubbell" authorityYear="1993" box="[490,646,1025,1046]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Nemoricantor" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0ABCEAA7FFCF8D02288CCE5C2CFCFBB1" box="[490,646,1025,1046]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="58">Nemoricantor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="FFC84D36FFCF8D022BC4CE5C2D7EFBB1" authorityName="Desutter-Grandcolas &amp; Hubbell" authorityYear="1993" box="[674,772,1025,1046]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Noctivox" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0ABCEAA7FFCF8D022BC4CE5C2D7EFBB1" box="[674,772,1025,1046]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="58">Noctivox</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="FFC84D36FFCF8D0229B0CE422F0FFB93" authorityName="Desutter-Grandcolas" authorityYear="1993" box="[214,373,1055,1076]" genus="Prolonguripes" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="2" pageNumber="58" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0ABCEAA7FFCF8D0229B0CE422F0FFB93" box="[214,373,1055,1076]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="58">Prolonguripes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="5C594B44FFCF8D0228E2CE422CC3FB93" author="Desutter-Grandcolas L" box="[388,697,1055,1077]" pageId="2" pageNumber="58" pagination="1 - 82" refId="ref5975" refString="Desutter-Grandcolas L. 1993. The cricket fauna of Chipanecan caves (Mexico), systematics, phylogeny and the evolution towards troglobitic life (Orthoptera, Grylloidea, Phalangopsidae, Luzarinae). International Journal of Speleology 22: 1 - 82." type="journal article" year="1993">Desutter-Grandcolas, 1993</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="5C594B44FFCF8D022BA3CE422C85FB92" author="Desutter-Grandcolas L" box="[709,767,1055,1077]" pageId="2" pageNumber="58" pagination="1 - 19" refId="ref6090" refString="Desutter-Grandcolas L. 1999. Are troglobitic taxa troglobiomorphic? A tes using phylogenetic inference. International Journal of Speleology 26: 1 - 19." type="journal article" year="1999">1999</bibRefCitation>
). The monophyly of this group is well supported by the apical migration of sclerites in the epiphallic arms (termed the ‘C-sclerites’ by 
<bibRefCitation id="5C594B44FFCF8D022B71CE272EA1FB08" author="Desutter-Grandcolas L" pageId="2" pageNumber="58" pagination="1 - 82" refId="ref5975" refString="Desutter-Grandcolas L. 1993. The cricket fauna of Chipanecan caves (Mexico), systematics, phylogeny and the evolution towards troglobitic life (Orthoptera, Grylloidea, Phalangopsidae, Luzarinae). International Journal of Speleology 22: 1 - 82." type="journal article" year="1993">Desutter-Grandcolas, 1993</bibRefCitation>
) and the endophallic apodeme without a mediodorsal crest. The group includes some 84 species in the aforementioned genera, distributed throughout Central America and the West Indies.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="387736B5FFCF8D0229DACF4E2DB9FE48" blockId="2.[164,779,810,1903]" lastBlockId="2.[826,1441,198,495]" pageId="2" pageNumber="58">
<bibRefCitation id="5C594B44FFCF8D0229DACF4E2F0AFA8D" author="Hubbell TH" box="[188,368,1299,1322]" pageId="2" pageNumber="58" pagination="191 - 233" refId="ref6412" refString="Hubbell TH. 1938. New cave-crickets from Yucatan, with a review of the Pentacentrinae, and studies on the genus Amphiacusta (Orthoptera: Gryllidae). Carnegie Institute of Washington Publication 491: 191 - 233." type="journal article" year="1938">Hubbell (1938)</bibRefCitation>
formed the name Amphiacustae using his standard suffix for family-group names beneath the rank of subfamily and although the group has been intensively studied since then (
<bibRefCitation id="5C594B44FFCF8D0229CDCFD32F90FA04" author="Desutter-Grandcolas L" box="[171,490,1422,1444]" pageId="2" pageNumber="58" pagination="1 - 82" refId="ref5975" refString="Desutter-Grandcolas L. 1993. The cricket fauna of Chipanecan caves (Mexico), systematics, phylogeny and the evolution towards troglobitic life (Orthoptera, Grylloidea, Phalangopsidae, Luzarinae). International Journal of Speleology 22: 1 - 82." type="journal article" year="1993">Desutter-Grandcolas, 1993</bibRefCitation>
, 1997, 1999; Desutter- Grandcolas &amp; Otte, 1997), it has never been assigned a rank. Thus, 
<bibRefCitation id="5C594B44FFCF8D022820CF962C7BFA46" author="Hubbell TH" box="[326,513,1483,1505]" pageId="2" pageNumber="58" pagination="191 - 233" refId="ref6412" refString="Hubbell TH. 1938. New cave-crickets from Yucatan, with a review of the Pentacentrinae, and studies on the genus Amphiacusta (Orthoptera: Gryllidae). Carnegie Institute of Washington Publication 491: 191 - 233." type="journal article" year="1938">Hubbell’s (1938)</bibRefCitation>
original spelling of the name (using the suffix -ae) has never been questioned. The suffixes of family-group names are regulated by the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature (
<collectionCode id="5ED9AE70FFCF8D0229CDCC1B2E96F9FB" box="[171,236,1606,1628]" pageId="2" pageNumber="58">ICZN</collectionCode>
) at the ranks of superfamily, family, subfamily, tribe, and subtribe (
<collectionCode id="5ED9AE70FFCF8D0228FDCC392FA4F9DE" box="[411,478,1636,1657]" pageId="2" pageNumber="58">ICZN</collectionCode>
, 1999: article 29.2). The suffixes of names at other ranks within the family group are not formally regulated, but do have widely accepted standard suffixes (e.g. -oidae for an epifamily, -iti for a supertribe, -ita for an infratribe, etc.). The suffixes of rankless taxa are likewise unregulated by the 
<collectionCode id="5ED9AE70FFCF8D02299ECD412F40F896" box="[248,314,1820,1841]" pageId="2" pageNumber="58">ICZN</collectionCode>
, and their use has become increasingly desirable in recent years because of the widespread use of cladistic methodology and the need to name important nodes within phylogenies; particularly in cases where the assignment of a specific rank would be superfluous. Nevertheless, the use of the name Amphiacustae as a rankless taxon retaining its original suffix is somewhat problematic because of the similarity of the name with that of the 
<typeStatus id="E7738817FFCF8D022C7CCB022B31FED3" box="[1306,1355,351,372]" pageId="2" pageNumber="58">type</typeStatus>
genus. This has the potential to cause confusion, and so the group is here assigned the rank of subtribe and the suffix is emended to ‘-ina’, in accordance with 
<collectionCode id="5ED9AE70FFCF8D022C04CBE62BDBFE77" box="[1378,1441,443,464]" pageId="2" pageNumber="58">ICZN</collectionCode>
regulations.
</paragraph>
